Can systemic risks be regulated ?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden shifts in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because, coming out of the crisis, the global economy is unbalanced in many ways, particularly in terms of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the origin of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Above all, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when no more credit is available) is, and will probably remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without prior warning signs.
Periodic displays of instability exact a high social cost from those least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat itself, it could erode trust in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of trust that could signal excessive regulation, state control and disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a crisis of sovereign debt of advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can translate into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a decline in tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenses.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "tax packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary counter-cyclical measures.
Unseen imbalances and systemic risks make policies that seem prudent in fact not prudent.
For example, Spain had not had a fiscal deficit at the start of the crisis.
But his income and expenses were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also trigger a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative impact on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is no doubt a typical example.
In the end, the only exit is to reset the value of assets through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can trigger this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and taking swift corrective measures.
Detailed new legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection and dispute resolution mechanisms are soon to be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will in no way solve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and announcing instability.
In addition to and in complement of new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
Some top politicians and analysts, however, believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex and permanently evolving global financial system make risk detection, in their view, either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If skeptics are right, we then have to accept that we will occasionally be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than the one we thought necessary barely three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists in rejecting a true proposition and the other is in accepting a false proposition.
Let's call the RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question may be posed in these terms: in the context of risk detection and response to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the most probable high cost ?
Those opposed to prudent monitoring of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable sign announcing a potentially growing instability.
Wasting time looking for such a sign.
Instability occurs instantaneously.
But this position appears flawed.
During the 2008 crisis, for example, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note.
One must however admit that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not foresee the point of no return.
They were nonetheless unmistakable signs.
The second position is that there are many warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF is likely to be more expensive than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the cure is worse than the disease.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
However, RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the aggregated negative effect of a false-positive reaction (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I'm not convinced, for my part.
There may be a deeper trend at work.
Whether it's in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and mistakes are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be the opposite, namely that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, related to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refrain from acting unless having good reasons to do so.
However, in the light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at the very least debatable.
Based on new theories and experiments, we may eventually conclude that systemic risk political responses are impossible to develop and that the cost of ASQ errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try the experiment, and give responsibility to a new institution, or an existing one, with access to relevant information, with sharp analytical skills both at the financial and macroeconomic levels, and relatively protected from conflicts of interest.
His analysis should be made public and could thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the financial system's ability to regulate itself.
